text:
Park Avenue, north from East 52nd Street, showing an early view of this thoroughfare prior to the enclosure of the railroad tracks shown. At the right is the Steinway Piano factory at the S. E. corner of 53rd Street. The fenced lot on the left is at the N. W. corner of 52nd St.

About 1900

Park Avenue, north from 52nd Street, before electrification and covering over of the upper end of the railroad yards. The growth of the railroad has resulted in destruction of the old tunnel and Avenue between 56th Street and 49th Street, where the old yards originally ended.
By 1910 the Avenue will be reopened down to this point.
The Steinway Piano factory, dating back to the Civil war decade, will be demolished in 1911.
The small house on the N.E. corner of 53rd Street will stand there till 1924.
The Racquet and Tennis Club will occupy the block opposite the Steinway factory, but the small houses on the west side between 53rd and 54th Streets will still be standing thirty years later.
Compare with Galloway's photograph of the identical scene in 1932. 1905.

Ewing Galloway, Photographer.

April 3, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

Park Avenue, north on east side, from 52nd Street.
The first building at the right is the Montana Apartments, built in 1912 on the site of the old Steinway factory.
The N. E. corner of 53rd Street is new, about 1925.
383 Park Avenue, just above it, was built in 1911 and is now oldest building in the block.
Further north No. 441, the small dark building on the N. E. corner of 56th Street (about 1880) contrasts with the new Ritz Tower Apartment Building at 57th Street, erected 1927.
October 28, 1930.

P.L. Sperr, Photographer.

Park Avenue, north from 52nd Street. The Racquet and Tennis Club occupies the block in the west side between 52nd and 53rd Street. To the right of it there is just a glimpse of the Fuller Building tower at Madison Avenue and 57th Street. On the east side of the Avenue the Ritz Tower rises at 57th Street. Careful comparison with Galloway's photograph of the identical scene in 1905 will show that the small buildings on the west side of the avenue, between 53rd and 54th Streets, are the identical ones shown in the earlier picture. The small apartment house (No. 441) on the N. E. corner of 56th Street is also an old building. 1932. Ewing Galloway
